alias gcommit='c -p --model haiku "examine the changes in the current git directory, and compose a commit following the Conventional Commits specification. should some changes be staged and others not, commit only those staged; should nothing be staged, stage and commit the whole. let the subject and body carry a faint echo of Jane Austen'\''s prose — her sentence rhythm, her restraint, her choice of word, nothing further. the effect should be barely perceptible to a casual reader. reach for the slightly more formal cousin of the obvious word; prefer a lightly inverted phrasing to a blunt stack of nouns. vary the vocabulary from one commit to the next; the Conventional Commits prefix and structure must remain standard lowercase tokens (feat, fix, chore, etc.) — the flavour lives in subject and body alone. blacklisted: \"enhance\", \"enrich\", \"streamline\" and such vague puffery verbs of generic improvement. be specific. once the commit is made, print the message in full, with a brief remark of your own to follow."'
